es Upcoming South Africa Tour Due To Coronavirus|date=2020-03-20|website=ProWrestling.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n\n'''Religious'''\n*[[Zion Christian Church]] (ZCC) Easter pilgrimage, cancelled until further notice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/trips-to-moria-on-hold-until-further-notice-over-coronavirus-pandemic-zcc-tells-congregants-20200317|title=Trips to Moria on hold until further notice over coronavirus pandemic, ZCC tells congregants|website=news24.com|date=17 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n*[[Muslim Judicial Council]] (MJC) suspends [[Friday prayer]]<nowiki/>s but keeps mosques open. As of Sunday, 22 March, mosques have closed but the call to prayer will still be given.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-mjc-suspends-jumuah-prayers-but-no-call-to-close-mosques-20200318|title=Coronavirus: MJC suspends Jumuah prayers, but no call to close mosques|date=2020-03-18|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*Chief Rabbi [[Warren Goldstein]] suspends Synagogues.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Africa's shuls close to stop spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.sajr.co.za/news-and-articles/2020/03/19/south-africa-s-shuls-close-to-stop-spread-of-coronavirus |work=South Africa Jewish Report |access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Traditional circumcision schools in Eastern Cape suspended.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sizani |first1=Mkhuseli |title=Coronavirus: Traditional circumcision schools in Eastern Cape suspended |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-traditional-circumcision-schools-in-eastern-cape-suspended-20200323 |access-date=|website=News24}}</ref>\n\n'''Expo & Trade shows'''\n*HuntEx, postponed until unknown future date.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huntex.net/|title=HuntEx2020 {{!}} Ten Years Inspiring Adventure|website=www.huntex.net|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*DecorEx Cape Town & Durban, postponed until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://decorex.co.za/|title=HOME|website=Decorex Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*Tyrexpo, postponed to 4\u20136 August 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tyrexpoafrica.com/attention.php|title=Tyrexpo Africa 2020|website=www.tyrexpoafrica.com|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n*Power & Electricity World expo, postponed until 20\u201321 August 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.terrapinn.com/exhibition/power-electricity-world-africa/Event-Postponement.stm|title=Event Postponement {{!}} Power & Electricity|date=2020-03-23|website=Power & Electricity World Africa 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\n'''Other'''\n*[[University of Pretoria]], [[University of Cape Town]], [[Stellenbosch University]], [[Rhodes University]], [[University of KwaZulu Natal]] and [[Durban University of Technology]] graduation ceremonies cancelled or postponed until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ewn.co.za/2020/03/13/stellenbosch-uct-cancel-upcoming-graduations-due-to-coronavirus|title=STELLENBOSCH, UCT CANCEL UPCOMING GRADUATIONS DUE TO CORONAVIRUS|last1=Kassen|first1=Jarita|website=EWN|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/coronavirus-in-sa-uct-graduations-suspended-amid-covid-19-concerns-20200314|title=Coronavirus in SA: UCT graduations suspended amid Covid-19 concerns|last1=McCain|first1=Nicole|website=News24|date=14 March 2020|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sowetanlive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-03-16-universities-cancelling-in-person-classes-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Universities cancelling in-person classes due to coronavirus|website=SowetanLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.up.ac.za/news/post_2881150-update-postponement-of-contact-classes-and-rescheduling-of-academic-calendar- |title = UPDATE: Postponement of contact classes and rescheduling of academic calendar}}</ref>\n*[[List of comic book conventions|Comic Con]] Cape Town, postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/whats-on/cape-town/comic-con-cape-town-postponed-to-2021-45138721|title=Comic Con Cape Town postponed to 2021|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*Agricultural events such as the [[Pietermaritzburg]] Royal Show, SA Cheese Festival, Qualit\u00e9 Awards Dinner, and Agri-Expo Western Cape Youth Show, cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodformzansi.co.za/covid-19-farmers-urged-to-protect-themselves-workers/|title=COVID-19: Farmers urged to protect themselves, workers|last=Ngcakani|first=Noluthando|date=2020-03-16|website=Food For Mzansi|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] [[Lifesaving South Africa]], national championships cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/wimpy-lifesaving-south-africa-national-championships-cancelled-44956403|title=Wimpy Lifesaving South Africa National Championships cancelled|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Scouts South Africa]], all Scouting activity suspended until schools reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scouts.org.za/2020/03/16/scouting-suspended-in-response-to-covid-19/|title=Scouting suspended in response to COVID-19|website=www.scouts.org.za|date=16 March 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[Johannesburg|City of Johannesburg]], all public facilities closed indefinitely including public swimming pools, recreational and civic centres, stadiums, libraries, sporting facilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than {{val|7500}} MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> \n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer \u2013 here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation ==\n{{Main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe spreading of [[fake news]] and other misinformation in South Africa about the virus is an offence punishable with either a fine, six months' imprisonment, or both.<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" />\n\nThe arrival of the COVID-19 virus in South Africa saw an increase in the dissemination of misinformation about the virus on social media and other platforms. These range from messages minimising the virus's harm in the country<ref name=\"MaverickFake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-31-viral-outbreak-fake-news-spreads-in-sa-in-tandem-with-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus Fact Check#1: Viral outbreak: Fake news spreads in SA in tandem with Covid-19|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> to the propagation of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] about government actions to control the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fake-news-no-covid-19-testing-kits-are-not-contaminated-20200406|title=FAKE NEWS: No, Covid-19 testing kits are not contaminated|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=News24|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>   \n\nOne individual was arrested for posting a video showing himself drinking in public with friends following the national lockdown whilst stating that there was \"nothing called corona here\".<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" /> In another incident a man claimed that 10,000 government officials would be going door-to-door using contaminated test kits to test people for the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\" /> A conspiracy theory that [[Bill Gates]] wished to test a COVID-19 \"vaccine\" in Africa or South Africa first caused significant controversy on social media<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-06-bill-gates-trevor-noah-death-threats--that-vaccine-how-it-all-went-wrong/|title=Bill Gates, Trevor Noah, death threats & that vaccine: how it all went wrong|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> following the publication of a now retracted story in [[News24]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-the-bill-and-melinda-gates-foundation-for-africa-vaccine-story-20200405|title=Apology to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation for 'Africa vaccine' story|date=2020-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[Trevor Noah]] stated that he received hate mail for conducting the interview on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' with Gates where it was falsely reported that Gates made the claim.<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\" /> \n\nFake news that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of COVID-19 symptoms also spread in the country during this period as it also did in other countries around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says '5G causing Covid-19 deaths' is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Africa|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/ National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Government COVID-19 website]\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 Government officials' speeches]\n*[https://datastudio.google.com/u/0/reporting/1b60bdc7-bec7-44c9-ba29-be0e043d8534/page/hrUIB Dashboard by Data Science for Social Impact Research Group, University of Pretoria]\n*[https://coronamap.co.za Corona virus map]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 World Health Organization (WHO) COVID-19 pandemic information]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Shaze", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor updated to testing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Kakodhiq", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement AL\n|type               = vi\n|official_name      = Kakodhiq\n|other_name         = Kakodiki\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|county             = [[Vlor\u00eb County|Vlor\u00eb]]\n|municipality       = [[Delvin\u00eb]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39|58|23|N|20|06|24|E|type:settlement|display=inline,title}}\n|car_plates         = DL\n|elevation          = 620\n|website            = \n}}\n\n'''Kakodhiq''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b9}}; [[Romanization of Greek|romanized]]: ''Kakod\u00edqi'' or ''Kakod\u00edki'') is a village in [[Vlor\u00eb County]], southern [[Albania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geonames.org/search.html?q=Kakodhiq&country=AL|title=Location of Kakodhiq}}</ref> At the 2015 local government reform it became part of the municipality of [[Delvin\u00eb]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |title=Law nr. 115/2014 |access-date=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is inhabited solely by [[Greeks in Albania|Greeks]].<ref name=Kallivretakis>{{cite web|last1=Kallivretakis|first1=Leonidas|title=\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u039a\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c5\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0393\u03b5\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 [The Greek Community of Albania in Terms of Historical Geography and Demography]|url=http://helios-eie.ekt.gr/EIE/handle/10442/8696|publisher=\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03a3\u03b9\u03b4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2|accessdate=2 February 2015|page=54|language=Greek|date=1995}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAccording to [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] statistics, the village had 443 inhabitants in 1895.<ref name=kokolakis>\u039c\u03b9\u03c7\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2, \"[http://helios-eie.ekt.gr/EIE/bitstream/10442/7682/1/N02.018.09.pdf \u0397 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0397\u03c0\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03ad \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 1895]\" \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b3\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2, \u039b\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b1\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03b2\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2, \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03ae\u03c4\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03b7\u03c4\u03c1\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2, \u039c\u03b9\u03c7\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0395\u03c5\u03b4\u03bf\u03ba\u03af\u03b1 \u039f\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03c0\u03af\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 (\u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc.), ''\u03a0\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u03c7\u03ce\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5. \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1'', \u0399\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf \u039d\u03b5\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u0395\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd/\u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u038a\u03b4\u03c1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1 \u0395\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd, Athens 2003, p. 287</ref> The village had 211 inhabitants in 1993, all ethnically [[Greeks]].<ref name=Kallivretakis /> The village today has a permanent population of roughly 50-100 inhabitants, notably due to migration to [[Greece]] or other countries. Despite this, the population doubles in [[Easter]], [[Summer]] and [[Christmas]], as most people return to their village to celebrate or have holidays with their families.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Delvin\u00eb div}}\n{{Northern Epirus}}\n[[Category:Northern Epirus]]\n[[Category:Villages in Vlor\u00eb County]]\n[[Category:Greek communities in Albania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement AL\n|type               = vi\n|official_name      = Kakodhiq\n|other_name         = Kakodiki\n|image_skyline      = \n|image_caption      = \n|county             = [[Vlor\u00eb County|Vlor\u00eb]]\n|municipality       = [[Delvin\u00eb]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|39|58|23|N|20|06|24|E|type:settlement|display=inline,title}}\n|car_plates         = DL\n|elevation          = 620\n|website            = \n}}\n\n'''Kakodhiq''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03b4\u03af\u03ba\u03b9}}; [[Romanization of Greek|romanized]]: ''Kakod\u00edqi'' or ''Kakod\u00edki'') is a village in [[Vlor\u00eb County]], southern [[Albania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geonames.org/search.html?q=Kakodhiq&country=AL|title=Location of Kakodhiq}}</ref> At the 2015 local government reform it became part of the municipality of [[Delvin\u00eb]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |title=Law nr. 115/2014 |access-date=2019-07-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It is inhabited solely by [[Greeks in Albania|Greeks]].<ref name=Kallivretakis>{{cite web|last1=Kallivretakis|first1=Leonidas|title=\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u039a\u03bf\u03b9\u03bd\u03cc\u03c4\u03b7\u03c4\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0391\u03bb\u03b2\u03b1\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03c5\u03c0\u03cc \u03c4\u03bf \u03a0\u03c1\u03af\u03c3\u03bc\u03b1 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u0393\u03b5\u03c9\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 [The Greek Community of Albania in Terms of Historical Geography and Demography]|url=http://helios-eie.ekt.gr/EIE/handle/10442/8696|publisher=\u0395\u03ba\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9\u03c2 \u03a3\u03b9\u03b4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2|accessdate=2 February 2015|page=54|language=Greek|date=1995}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nAccording to [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] statistics, the village had 443 inhabitants in 1895.<ref name=kokolakis>\u039c\u03b9\u03c7\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2, \"[http://helios-eie.ekt.gr/EIE/bitstream/10442/7682/1/N02.018.09.pdf \u0397 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0397\u03c0\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u03a3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bd\u03b1\u03bc\u03ad \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 1895]\" \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u0392\u03b1\u03c3\u03af\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b3\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2, \u039b\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd\u03af\u03b4\u03b1\u03c2 \u039a\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03b2\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2, \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03ae\u03c4\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03b7\u03c4\u03c1\u03cc\u03c0\u03bf\u03c5\u03bb\u03bf\u03c2, \u039c\u03b9\u03c7\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0395\u03c5\u03b4\u03bf\u03ba\u03af\u03b1 \u039f\u03bb\u03c5\u03bc\u03c0\u03af\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 (\u03b5\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc.), ''\u03a0\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03c5\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03bf\u03b9\u03ba\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03bf\u03af \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u03c7\u03ce\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5. \u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac \u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03c4\u03ae\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1'', \u0399\u03bd\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf \u039d\u03b5\u03bf\u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ce\u03bd \u0395\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd/\u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u038a\u03b4\u03c1\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1 \u0395\u03c1\u03b5\u03c5\u03bd\u03ce\u03bd, Athens 2003, p. 287</ref> \u03a4he village had 211 inhabitants in 1993, all ethnically [[Greeks]].<ref name=Kallivretakis /> The village today has a permanent population of roughly 50-100 inhabitants, notably due to migration to [[Greece]] or other countries. Despite this, the population doubles in [[Easter]], [[Summer]] and [[Christmas]], as most people return to their village to celebrate or have holidays with their families.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Delvin\u00eb div}}\n{{Northern Epirus}}\n[[Category:Northern Epirus]]\n[[Category:Villages in Vlor\u00eb County]]\n[[Category:Greek communities in Albania]]\n", "name_user": "Graham87", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kakodhiq"}
{"title_page": "And Then There Were None (miniseries)", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = And Then There Were None\n| image                = And then there were none Title card.jpg\n| image_alt            = Series title with ten crumbled Jade figurines\n| caption              = Title card\n| genre                = {{plainlist|\n* [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]]\n* [[Television drama series|Drama]]\n* [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]}}\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[And Then There Were None]]''|[[Agatha Christie]]}}\n| writer               = [[Sarah Phelps]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Craig Viveiros]]\n| starring             = {{plainlist|\n*[[Douglas Booth]]\n*[[Charles Dance]]\n*[[Maeve Dermody]]\n*[[Burn Gorman]]\n*[[Anna Maxwell Martin]]\n*[[Sam Neill]]\n*[[Miranda Richardson]]\n*[[Toby Stephens]]\n*[[Noah Taylor]]\n*[[Aidan Turner]]}}\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| composer             = Stuart Earl\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n| num_series           = \n| num_episodes         = 3\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Mathew Pritchard\n* Hilary Strong\n* Karen Thrussell\n* Damien Timmer\n* Matthew Read\n* Sara Phelps\n}}\n| producer             = Abi Bach\n| editor               = \n| cinematography       = John Pardue\n| runtime              = 180 minutes\n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mammoth Screen]]\n* Agatha Christie Productions\n* [[Acorn DVD|Acorn Productions]]\n* [[A&E Networks]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[BBC]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[BBC One]]\n* [[BBC One HD]]\n}}\n| picture_format       = [[HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2015|12|26|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2015|12|28|df=y}}\n| website              = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06v2v52\n}}\n\n'''''And Then There Were None''''' is a 2015 [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]] [[miniseries|television serial]] that was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] from 26 to 28 December 2015. The three-part programme was adapted by [[Sarah Phelps]] and directed by [[Craig Viveiros]] and is based on [[Agatha Christie]]'s [[And Then There Were None|novel of the same name]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/28/david-walliams-agatha-christie-drama-bbc|title=David Walliams to star as BBC bags Agatha Christie drama deal|work=The Guardian|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Plunkett, John}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-02-28/david-walliams-heralds-new-era-for-bbc-as-the-new-home-of-agatha-christie-adaptations|title=David Walliams heralds new era for BBC as the new home of Agatha Christie adaptations|work=Radio Times|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Dowell, Ben}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/david-walliams-to-star-in-new-agatha-christie-bbc-drama-9161210.html|title=David Walliams to star in new Agatha Christie BBC drama|work=Independent|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> The series features an [[ensemble cast]], including [[Douglas Booth]], [[Charles Dance]], [[Maeve Dermody]], [[Burn Gorman]], [[Anna Maxwell Martin]], [[Sam Neill]], [[Miranda Richardson]], [[Toby Stephens]], [[Noah Taylor]] and [[Aidan Turner]]. The programme follows a group of strangers who are invited to a secluded island where they are murdered one by one for their past crimes.\n\nThe serial, debuting to 6 million viewers, received critical acclaim with many praising the writing, performances, and cinematography. It also scored high ratings.\n\n==Synopsis==\nOn a hot day in late August 1939, eight people, all strangers to each other, are invited to a small, isolated island off the coast of [[Devon]], England, called Soldier's Island, by a \"Mr. and Mrs. Owen\". The guests settle in at the manor home on the island tended by two newly hired servants, a husband and wife, Mr. Thomas Rogers and Mrs. Ethel Rogers, but their hosts are absent. When the guests sit down to dinner, they notice the [[centrepiece]], ten abstract art deco figurines of jade, supposedly representing ten soldiers arranged in a circle. Afterward, Mr. Rogers puts on a [[gramophone record]], from which a voice accuses everyone present of a murder.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.agathachristie.com/news/article/filming-begins-on-agatha-christies-and-then-there|title= Filming begins on Agatha Christie's ''And Then There Were None''|website= agathachristie.com|accessdate= 24 December 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151116143425/http://www.agathachristie.com/news/article/filming-begins-on-agatha-christies-and-then-there|archive-date= 16 November 2015|url-status=dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Shortly after this, one of the party dies from poisoning, and then more and more people are murdered, all in methods synonymous with a poem affixed to the back of each bedroom door. With each death, the murderer removes a figurine from the centerpiece to coincide with the rhyme's sinister disappearance of each \"little soldier boy\". The remaining people decide to work together. They must discover who the murderer is before they run out of time and nobody remains.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Douglas Booth]] as Anthony James Marston\n* [[Charles Dance]] as Justice Lawrence John Wargrave\n* [[Maeve Dermody]] as Vera Elizabeth Claythorne\n* [[Burn Gorman]] as Detective Sergeant William Henry Blore\n* [[Anna Maxwell Martin]] as Ethel Rogers\n* [[Sam Neill]] as General John Gordon Macarthur\n* [[Miranda Richardson]] as Emily Caroline Brent\n* [[Toby Stephens]] as Doctor Edward George Armstrong\n* [[Noah Taylor]] as Thomas Rogers\n* [[Aidan Turner]] as Philip Lombard\n* Harley Gallacher as Cyril Ogilvie Hamilton\n* Paul Chahidi as Isaac Morris\n* Charlie Russell as Audrey\n* Richard Hansell as Recording Artist\n* Christopher Hatherall as Fred Narracott\n* Ben Deery as Henry Richmond\n* Margot Edwards as Miss Brady\n* [[Rob Heaps]] as Hugo Hamilton \n* Celia Henebury as Leslie Macarthur\n* Tom Clegg as Landor\n* Daisy Waterstone as Beatrice\n* Catherine Bailey as Olivia Ogilvie Hamilton\n* Joseph Prowen as Edward Seton\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Conception===\n{{multiple image|perrow = 3|total_width=400\n | image1 = Douglas Booth - February 2011 - crop.jpg |width1=100|height1=110\n | alt1 = Douglas Booth\n | image2 =Miranda Richardson Met Opera 2010 Shankbone.jpg |width2=100|height2=125\n | alt2 = Miranda Richardson\n | image3 =Charles Dance 2012 (cropped).jpg |width3=100|height3=100\n | alt3 = Charles Dance\n | image4 =Maeve Dermody.jpg |width4=100|height4=140\n | alt4 = Maeve Dermody\n | image5 =Sam Neill 2010.jpg |width5=100|height5=125\n | alt5 = Sam Neill\n | image6 =Aidan Turner bearded.jpg |width6=100|height6=90\n | alt6 = Aidan Turner\n | footer = (''From top to bottom, left to right''), Douglas Booth, Miranda Richardson, Charles Dance, Maeve Dermody, Sam Neill and Aidan Turner.\n}}\n\n''And Then There Were None'' was commissioned by [[Ben Stephenson]] and [[Charlotte Moore (TV executive)|Charlotte Moore]] for the BBC to mark the 125th anniversary of Agatha Christie's birth.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/agatha-christie.html|title=BBC One to become new home of Agatha Christie in UK|work=BBC|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> The adaptation was produced by [[Mammoth Screen]] in partnership with Agatha Christie Productions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bbc-commissions-two-new-agatha-684037|title=BBC Commissions Two New Agatha Christie Adaptations|work=Hollywood Reporter|date=27 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Kemp, Stuart}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/bbc-plots-two-agatha-christie-adaptations-for-writers-125th-anniversary-1201123100|title=BBC Plots Agatha Christie Adaptations for Writer's 125th Anniversary|work=Variety|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Barraclough, Leo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/bbc-signs-agatha-christie-deal/5068155.article|title=BBC signs Agatha Christie deal|work=Broadcast|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Kanter, Jake}}</ref>\n\nWriter [[Sarah Phelps]] told the BBC that she was shocked by the starkness and brutality of the novel. Comparing the novel to Christie's other work, she stated, \"Within the Marple and Poirot stories somebody is there to unravel the mystery, and that gives you a sense of safety and security, of predicting what is going to happen next... In this book that doesn't happen \u2013 no one is going to come to save you, absolutely nobody is coming to help or rescue or interpret\".<ref name=\"BBC Online Writers' Room\">{{cite web|author=Staff|title=Adapting Agatha Christie's 'And Then There Were None' for BBC One|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/writersroom/entries/8010ddc5-83eb-418c-9cf3-95cb6cfc8709|date=17 December 2015|website=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nMaeve Dermody was cast two days before the read through of the script and was in [[Myanmar]] at the time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dermody|first1=Maeve|title=Maeve Dermody plays Vera Claythorne|url=http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/maeve-dermody|website=Agatha Christie.com|accessdate=29 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731072218/http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/maeve-dermody|archive-date=31 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> She flew to the UK to begin work with a dialect coach and read the book in the first two weeks of filming.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dermody|first1=Maeve|title=Behind the scenes|url=http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/behind-the-scenes-of-and-then-there-were-none|website=Agatha Christie.com|accessdate=29 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007210719/http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/behind-the-scenes-of-and-then-there-were-none|archive-date=7 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in July 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/then-there-were-none|title=Filming begins on Agatha Christie's And Then There Were None for BBC One|work=BBC|date=10 July 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> [[Cornwall]] was used for many of the harbour and beach scenes, including [[Holywell Bay]], [[Kynance Cove]], and [[Mullion Cove]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.westbriton.co.uk/Poldark-Aidan-Turner-Cornwall-Charles-Dance-Sam/story-27465651-detail/story.html|title=Not Poldark: Aidan Turner back in Cornwall with Charles Dance and Sam Neill in Agatha Christie drama|work=West Briton|date=22 July 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807225234/http://www.westbriton.co.uk/Poldark-Aidan-Turner-Cornwall-Charles-Dance-Sam/story-27465651-detail/story.html|archive-date=7 August 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Harefield#Manor of Harefield|Harefield House]] in [[Hillingdon]], outside [[London]], served as the location for the island mansion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thelocationguide.com/blog/2015/12/bbc%E2%80%99s-and-then-there-were-none-filmed-in-cornwall-and-hillingdon/|title=BBC's And Then There Were None filmed in Cornwall and Hillingdon|work=The Location Guide|date=22 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015|author=Tom Deehan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113202216/http://www.thelocationguide.com/blog/2015/12/bbc%E2%80%99s-and-then-there-were-none-filmed-in-cornwall-and-hillingdon/|archive-date=13 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Production designer Sophie Beccher decorated the house in the style of 1930s designers like [[Syrie Maugham]] and [[Elsie de Wolfe]].<ref>{{cite press release|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=And Then There Were None: A Landmark Adaptation of the World's Best SElling Crime Novel|url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/attwn-media-pack.pdf|publisher=BBC|date=December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> The below stairs and kitchen scenes were shot at Wrotham Park in Hertfordshire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agathachristie.com/news/2016/and-then-there-were-none-and-previous-adaptation-links|title=And Then There Were None and Christie Adaptation Links|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref> Railway scenes were filmed at the [[South Devon Railway (heritage railway)|South Devon Railway]] between Totnes and Buckfastleigh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Steam-railway-ratings-winner/story-28484656-detail/story.html|title=Steam railway is a star in Christie's ratings winner|publisher=Western Morning News|date=8 January 2016|accessdate=29 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112070339/http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Steam-railway-ratings-winner/story-28484656-detail/story.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table\n|background = #9F260E\n|overall     = \n|title      = \n|director   = \n|writer     = \n|airdate    = \n|viewers    = \n|country    = UK\n|episodes   = \n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = Episode 1\n| DirectedBy      = Craig Viveiros\n| WrittenBy       = Sarah Phelps\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|12|26|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 9.56<ref name=\"BARB_Top30\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30|title=Top 30 Programmes|publisher=BARB|date=14 February 2016|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref><ref group=lower-alpha name=28day>28 day data</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = In August 1939, eight strangers arrive at Soldier Island, most having ostensibly been invited by old friends or the current ostensible owners, Mr and Mrs Owen. There is no host to greet them but there are domestic staff, Thomas and Ethel Rogers, a married couple. The \"guests\" find a copy of a children's rhyme, \"[[Ten Little Indians|Ten Little Soldiers]]\", in each of their rooms and ten jade figurines on the dining room table. After dinner, Mr Rogers, who had been instructed to do so, plays a gramophone record, in which all the guests as well as Mr and Mrs Rogers are named as being responsible for the death(s) of another human being for which they evaded punishment. One of the guests (Blore) is revealed to be an impostor using another name. Eight guests refute the accusations made against them, but Philip Lombard and Anthony Marston do not. Marston dies shortly thereafter from cyanide-laced gin in a similar manner to that of the first little soldier. The next day, the cook Mrs Rogers is found dead in her bed from unknown causes, matching the second verse from the poem. Vera Claythorne shows Dr Armstrong that two of the soldiers in the dining room have disappeared.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = Episode 2\n| DirectedBy      = Craig Viveiros\n| WrittenBy       = Sarah Phelps\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|12|27|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 8.45<ref name=\"BARB_Top30\"/><ref group=lower-alpha name=28day/>\n| ShortSummary    = The poisoning of both victims casts suspicion on Dr. Armstrong, who has his bag searched. As a hunt for the mysterious Mr Owen is conducted on the island, the nature behind the accusations begin to come to light; Philip Lombard confirms that he killed 21 Africans for a diamond reward, Emily Brent recounts the fateful past of her former maid, Beatrice Taylor, and General MacArthur succumbs to insanity, crippled with guilt over killing his subordinate and wife's lover, Arthur Richmond. After the General is found with his head smashed in with a telescope, the remaining seven realize that whoever left the mysterious message intends to make good on their threat, according to the rules of the [[Ten Little Indians|nursery rhyme]]. Wargrave proposes a damning theory to the others that the killer is one of them. After the butler, Mr Rogers, is found split open with an axe, and Miss Brent is impaled with one of her knitting needles, the five survivors band together to search all the rooms and belongings to unmask the killer and save themselves.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = Episode 3\n| DirectedBy      = Craig Viveiros\n| WrittenBy       = Sarah Phelps\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|12|28|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 8.33<ref name=\"BARB_Top30\"/><ref group=lower-alpha name=28day/>\n| ShortSummary    = Five of the original ten are left. Judge Wargrave is found, dressed up to match the Chancery verse of the poem, with a gunshot wound to the head. He is declared dead by Armstrong. The remaining four engage in a demented bacchanal with alcohol and drugs. Vera and Philip have sex. During the night, Armstrong leaves the house, leaving the other three to believe that he is the killer. Blore is ambushed and fatally stabbed by the killer wearing a bear skin rug. Subsequently, Armstrong's corpse is brought in by the tide. Vera manages to lift Philip's gun and when he charges at her, she shoots him dead. Delirious, she returns to her room where a noose is waiting. In a trance, she begins to hang herself. Then, Judge Wargrave walks in, quite alive, and reveals how he wanted to create an unsolvable mystery and punish the guilty, and how he intends to shoot himself to complete the poem. Vera tries to bargain with Wargrave, but he pulls the chair from under her and leaves her to die. He returns to the dining room, where he has set the table for two. He loads the revolver with the final bullet and shoots himself. The revolver recoils to land at the other table setting, thus creating a presumably unsolvable mystery for the police.\n| LineColor       =9F260E\n}}\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n''And Then There Were None'' received critical acclaim and was a ratings success for the BBC, with the first episode netting over 6 million viewers and becoming the second most watched programme on [[Boxing Day]]. Each of the two subsequent episodes netted over 5 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=Jasper|title=And Then There Were None helps BBC dominate Christmas ratings|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/dec/29/and-then-there-were-none-christmas-boxing-day-ratings-bbc-agatha-christie|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''And Then There Were None'' has an approval rating of 92% based on 13 reviews, with an average rating of 7.5/10. The site's critics' consensus reads: \"Dark yet dashingly executed, ''And Then There Were None'' offers a brazenly misanthropic look at human nature.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/and_then_there_were_none/s01|title=And Then There Were None: Miniseries|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite criticism ahead of the programme's launch from the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' that the production deviated from Agatha Christie's source material,<ref>{{cite news|title=What HAS the BBC done to Agatha Christie? Christmas viewers will be stunned by controversial new adaption featuring drugs, gruesome violence and the F-word|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3357749/What-BBC-Agatha-Christie.html|work=Daily Mail|first=Chris|last=Hastings|date=12 December 2015|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> ''And Then There Were None'' received critical acclaim. Ben Dowell of the ''[[Radio Times]]'' gave a positive review.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dowell|first=Ben|title=And Then There Were None is a creepy, chilling Agatha Christie... with a helping of Aidan Turner|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-12-26/and-then-there-were-none-is-a-creepy-chilling-agatha-christie-with-a-helping-of-aidan-turner|date=26 December 2015|work=[[Radio Times]]|location=London|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Jasper Reese for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave the first episode 4 out of 5 stars, calling it a \"pitch-black psychological thriller as teasing murder mystery\" and \"spiffingly watchable\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rees|first=Jasper|title=And Then There Were None, review: 'spiffingly watchable'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/12064725/And-Then-There-Were-None-review-spiffingly-watchable.html|date=26 December 2015|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nReviewing the first episode, UK daily newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Sam Wollaston noted, \"[...] it also manages to be loyal, not just in plot but in spirit as well. I think the queen of crime would approve. I certainly do. Mass murder rarely gets as fun as this.\"<ref name=\"The Guardian 26 December 2015\">{{cite news|last=Wollaston|first=Sam|title= Dickensian review \u2013 a labour of love obscured by too much fog and too many hats|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/dec/26/dickensian-agatha-christie-and-then-there-were-none-review|date=26 December 2015|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London, UK|accessdate= 29 December 2015}}</ref> Reviewing the final episode for ''The Daily Telegraph'', Tim Martin gave it 4 out of 5 stars, calling it a \"class act\", and praising the adaptation for highlighting the darkness of Christie's novel, which he claimed no previous adaptation had attempted.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Tim|title=And Then There Were None, episode three, review: 'a class act'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/12071655/And-Then-There-Were-None-episode-three-review.html|date=28 December 2015|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London, UK|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[And Then There Were None (disambiguation)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3581932|title=And Then There Were None}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes TV|and_then_there_were_none}}\n\n{{And Then There Were None}}\n\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:British crime films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British mystery films]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1930s]]\n[[Category:Television programmes based on works by Agatha Christie]]\n[[Category:BBC television dramas]]\n[[Category:Television series by Mammoth Screen]]\n[[Category:Films based on And Then There Were None]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name            = And Then There Were None\n| image                = And then there were none Title card.jpg\n| image_alt            = Series title with ten crumbled Jade figurines\n| caption              = Title card\n| genre                = {{plainlist|\n* [[Mystery fiction|Mystery]]\n* [[Television drama series|Drama]]\n* [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]}}\n| creator              = \n| based_on             = {{Based on|''[[And Then There Were None]]''|[[Agatha Christie]]}}\n| writer               = [[Sarah Phelps]]\n| screenplay           = \n| story                = \n| director             = [[Craig Viveiros]]\n| starring             = {{plainlist|\n*[[Douglas Booth]]\n*[[Charles Dance]]\n*[[Maeve Dermody]]\n*[[Burn Gorman]]\n*[[Anna Maxwell Martin]]\n*[[Sam Neill]]\n*[[Miranda Richardson]]\n*[[Toby Stephens]]\n*[[Noah Taylor]]\n*[[Aidan Turner]]}}\n| narrated             = \n| theme_music_composer = \n| composer             = Stuart Earl\n| country              = United Kingdom\n| language             = English\n| num_series           = \n| num_episodes         = 3\n| executive_producer   = {{Plainlist|\n* Mathew Pritchard\n* Hilary Strong\n* Karen Thrussell\n* Damien Timmer\n* Matthew Read\n* Sara Phelps\n}}\n| producer             = Abi Bach\n| editor               = \n| cinematography       = John Pardue\n| runtime              = 180 minutes\n| company              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Mammoth Screen]]\n* Agatha Christie Productions\n* [[Acorn DVD|Acorn Productions]]\n* [[A&E Networks]]\n}}\n| distributor          = [[BBC]]\n| budget               = \n| network              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[BBC One]]\n* [[BBC One HD]]\n}}\n| picture_format       = [[HDTV]] [[1080i]]\n| audio_format         = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired          = {{Start date|2015|12|26|df=y}}\n| last_aired           = {{End date|2015|12|28|df=y}}\n| website              = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b06v2v52\n}}\n\n'''''And Then There Were None''''' is a 2015 [[Mystery fiction|mystery]] [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]] [[miniseries|television serial]] that was first broadcast on [[BBC One]] from 26 to 28 December 2015. The three-part programme was adapted by [[Sarah Phelps]] and directed by Craig Viveiros and is based on [[Agatha Christie]]'s [[And Then There Were None|novel of the same name]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/feb/28/david-walliams-agatha-christie-drama-bbc|title=David Walliams to star as BBC bags Agatha Christie drama deal|work=The Guardian|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Plunkett, John}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2014-02-28/david-walliams-heralds-new-era-for-bbc-as-the-new-home-of-agatha-christie-adaptations|title=David Walliams heralds new era for BBC as the new home of Agatha Christie adaptations|work=Radio Times|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Dowell, Ben}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/david-walliams-to-star-in-new-agatha-christie-bbc-drama-9161210.html|title=David Walliams to star in new Agatha Christie BBC drama|work=Independent|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> The series features an [[ensemble cast]], including [[Douglas Booth]], [[Charles Dance]], [[Maeve Dermody]], [[Burn Gorman]], [[Anna Maxwell Martin]], [[Sam Neill]], [[Miranda Richardson]], [[Toby Stephens]], [[Noah Taylor]] and [[Aidan Turner]]. The programme follows a group of strangers who are invited to a secluded island where they are murdered one by one for their past crimes.\n\nThe serial, debuting to 6 million viewers, received critical acclaim with many praising the writing, performances, and cinematography. It also scored high ratings.\n\n==Synopsis==\nOn a hot day in late August 1939, eight people, all strangers to each other, are invited to a small, isolated island off the coast of [[Devon]], England, called Soldier's Island, by a \"Mr. and Mrs. Owen\". The guests settle in at the manor home on the island tended by two newly hired servants, a husband and wife, Mr. Thomas Rogers and Mrs. Ethel Rogers, but their hosts are absent. When the guests sit down to dinner, they notice the [[centrepiece]], ten abstract art deco figurines of jade, supposedly representing ten soldiers arranged in a circle. Afterward, Mr. Rogers puts on a [[gramophone record]], from which a voice accuses everyone present of a murder.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.agathachristie.com/news/article/filming-begins-on-agatha-christies-and-then-there|title= Filming begins on Agatha Christie's ''And Then There Were None''|website= agathachristie.com|accessdate= 24 December 2015|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151116143425/http://www.agathachristie.com/news/article/filming-begins-on-agatha-christies-and-then-there|archive-date= 16 November 2015|url-status=dead|df= dmy-all}}</ref> Shortly after this, one of the party dies from poisoning, and then more and more people are murdered, all in methods synonymous with a poem affixed to the back of each bedroom door. With each death, the murderer removes a figurine from the centerpiece to coincide with the rhyme's sinister disappearance of each \"little soldier boy\". The remaining people decide to work together. They must discover who the murderer is before they run out of time and nobody remains.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Douglas Booth]] as Anthony James Marston\n* [[Charles Dance]] as Justice Lawrence John Wargrave\n* [[Maeve Dermody]] as Vera Elizabeth Claythorne\n* [[Burn Gorman]] as Detective Sergeant William Henry Blore\n* [[Anna Maxwell Martin]] as Ethel Rogers\n* [[Sam Neill]] as General John Gordon Macarthur\n* [[Miranda Richardson]] as Emily Caroline Brent\n* [[Toby Stephens]] as Doctor Edward George Armstrong\n* [[Noah Taylor]] as Thomas Rogers\n* [[Aidan Turner]] as Philip Lombard\n* Harley Gallacher as Cyril Ogilvie Hamilton\n* Paul Chahidi as Isaac Morris\n* Charlie Russell as Audrey\n* Richard Hansell as Recording Artist\n* Christopher Hatherall as Fred Narracott\n* Ben Deery as Henry Richmond\n* Margot Edwards as Miss Brady\n* [[Rob Heaps]] as Hugo Hamilton \n* Celia Henebury as Leslie Macarthur\n* Tom Clegg as Landor\n* Daisy Waterstone as Beatrice\n* Catherine Bailey as Olivia Ogilvie Hamilton\n* Joseph Prowen as Edward Seton\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Conception===\n{{multiple image|perrow = 3|total_width=400\n | image1 = Douglas Booth - February 2011 - crop.jpg |width1=100|height1=110\n | alt1 = Douglas Booth\n | image2 =Miranda Richardson Met Opera 2010 Shankbone.jpg |width2=100|height2=125\n | alt2 = Miranda Richardson\n | image3 =Charles Dance 2012 (cropped).jpg |width3=100|height3=100\n | alt3 = Charles Dance\n | image4 =Maeve Dermody.jpg |width4=100|height4=140\n | alt4 = Maeve Dermody\n | image5 =Sam Neill 2010.jpg |width5=100|height5=125\n | alt5 = Sam Neill\n | image6 =Aidan Turner bearded.jpg |width6=100|height6=90\n | alt6 = Aidan Turner\n | footer = (''From top to bottom, left to right''), Douglas Booth, Miranda Richardson, Charles Dance, Maeve Dermody, Sam Neill and Aidan Turner.\n}}\n\n''And Then There Were None'' was commissioned by [[Ben Stephenson]] and [[Charlotte Moore (TV executive)|Charlotte Moore]] for the BBC to mark the 125th anniversary of Agatha Christie's birth.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2014/agatha-christie.html|title=BBC One to become new home of Agatha Christie in UK|work=BBC|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014}}</ref> The adaptation was produced by [[Mammoth Screen]] in partnership with Agatha Christie Productions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/bbc-commissions-two-new-agatha-684037|title=BBC Commissions Two New Agatha Christie Adaptations|work=Hollywood Reporter|date=27 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Kemp, Stuart}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/bbc-plots-two-agatha-christie-adaptations-for-writers-125th-anniversary-1201123100|title=BBC Plots Agatha Christie Adaptations for Writer's 125th Anniversary|work=Variety|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Barraclough, Leo}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/news/commissioning/bbc-signs-agatha-christie-deal/5068155.article|title=BBC signs Agatha Christie deal|work=Broadcast|date=28 February 2014|accessdate=3 April 2014|author=Kanter, Jake}}</ref>\n\nWriter [[Sarah Phelps]] told the BBC that she was shocked by the starkness and brutality of the novel. Comparing the novel to Christie's other work, she stated, \"Within the Marple and Poirot stories somebody is there to unravel the mystery, and that gives you a sense of safety and security, of predicting what is going to happen next... In this book that doesn't happen \u2013 no one is going to come to save you, absolutely nobody is coming to help or rescue or interpret\".<ref name=\"BBC Online Writers' Room\">{{cite web|author=Staff|title=Adapting Agatha Christie's 'And Then There Were None' for BBC One|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/writersroom/entries/8010ddc5-83eb-418c-9cf3-95cb6cfc8709|date=17 December 2015|website=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nMaeve Dermody was cast two days before the read through of the script and was in [[Myanmar]] at the time.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dermody|first1=Maeve|title=Maeve Dermody plays Vera Claythorne|url=http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/maeve-dermody|website=Agatha Christie.com|accessdate=29 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731072218/http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/maeve-dermody|archive-date=31 July 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> She flew to the UK to begin work with a dialect coach and read the book in the first two weeks of filming.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Dermody|first1=Maeve|title=Behind the scenes|url=http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/behind-the-scenes-of-and-then-there-were-none|website=Agatha Christie.com|accessdate=29 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161007210719/http://www.agathachristie.com/watch/and-then-there-were-none/behind-the-scenes-of-and-then-there-were-none|archive-date=7 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nFilming began in July 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2015/then-there-were-none|title=Filming begins on Agatha Christie's And Then There Were None for BBC One|work=BBC|date=10 July 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> [[Cornwall]] was used for many of the harbour and beach scenes, including [[Holywell Bay]], [[Kynance Cove]], and [[Mullion Cove]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.westbriton.co.uk/Poldark-Aidan-Turner-Cornwall-Charles-Dance-Sam/story-27465651-detail/story.html|title=Not Poldark: Aidan Turner back in Cornwall with Charles Dance and Sam Neill in Agatha Christie drama|work=West Briton|date=22 July 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807225234/http://www.westbriton.co.uk/Poldark-Aidan-Turner-Cornwall-Charles-Dance-Sam/story-27465651-detail/story.html|archive-date=7 August 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[Harefield#Manor of Harefield|Harefield House]] in [[Hillingdon]], outside [[London]], served as the location for the island mansion.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thelocationguide.com/blog/2015/12/bbc%E2%80%99s-and-then-there-were-none-filmed-in-cornwall-and-hillingdon/|title=BBC's And Then There Were None filmed in Cornwall and Hillingdon|work=The Location Guide|date=22 December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015|author=Tom Deehan|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113202216/http://www.thelocationguide.com/blog/2015/12/bbc%E2%80%99s-and-then-there-were-none-filmed-in-cornwall-and-hillingdon/|archive-date=13 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Production designer Sophie Beccher decorated the house in the style of 1930s designers like [[Syrie Maugham]] and [[Elsie de Wolfe]].<ref>{{cite press release|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|title=And Then There Were None: A Landmark Adaptation of the World's Best SElling Crime Novel|url=http://downloads.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/attwn-media-pack.pdf|publisher=BBC|date=December 2015|accessdate=27 December 2015}}</ref> The below stairs and kitchen scenes were shot at Wrotham Park in Hertfordshire.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agathachristie.com/news/2016/and-then-there-were-none-and-previous-adaptation-links|title=And Then There Were None and Christie Adaptation Links|date=29 February 2016|accessdate=30 October 2017}}</ref> Railway scenes were filmed at the [[South Devon Railway (heritage railway)|South Devon Railway]] between Totnes and Buckfastleigh.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Steam-railway-ratings-winner/story-28484656-detail/story.html|title=Steam railway is a star in Christie's ratings winner|publisher=Western Morning News|date=8 January 2016|accessdate=29 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112070339/http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Steam-railway-ratings-winner/story-28484656-detail/story.html|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table\n|background = #9F260E\n|overall     = \n|title      = \n|director   = \n|writer     = \n|airdate    = \n|viewers    = \n|country    = UK\n|episodes   = \n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = Episode 1\n| DirectedBy      = Craig Viveiros\n| WrittenBy       = Sarah Phelps\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|12|26|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 9.56<ref name=\"BARB_Top30\">{{cite web|url=http://www.barb.co.uk/whats-new/weekly-top-30|title=Top 30 Programmes|publisher=BARB|date=14 February 2016|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref><ref group=lower-alpha name=28day>28 day data</ref>\n| ShortSummary    = In August 1939, eight strangers arrive at Soldier Island, most having ostensibly been invited by old friends or the current ostensible owners, Mr and Mrs Owen. There is no host to greet them but there are domestic staff, Thomas and Ethel Rogers, a married couple. The \"guests\" find a copy of a children's rhyme, \"[[Ten Little Indians|Ten Little Soldiers]]\", in each of their rooms and ten jade figurines on the dining room table. After dinner, Mr Rogers, who had been instructed to do so, plays a gramophone record, in which all the guests as well as Mr and Mrs Rogers are named as being responsible for the death(s) of another human being for which they evaded punishment. One of the guests (Blore) is revealed to be an impostor using another name. Eight guests refute the accusations made against them, but Philip Lombard and Anthony Marston do not. Marston dies shortly thereafter from cyanide-laced gin in a similar manner to that of the first little soldier. The next day, the cook Mrs Rogers is found dead in her bed from unknown causes, matching the second verse from the poem. Vera Claythorne shows Dr Armstrong that two of the soldiers in the dining room have disappeared.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = Episode 2\n| DirectedBy      = Craig Viveiros\n| WrittenBy       = Sarah Phelps\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|12|27|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 8.45<ref name=\"BARB_Top30\"/><ref group=lower-alpha name=28day/>\n| ShortSummary    = The poisoning of both victims casts suspicion on Dr. Armstrong, who has his bag searched. As a hunt for the mysterious Mr Owen is conducted on the island, the nature behind the accusations begin to come to light; Philip Lombard confirms that he killed 21 Africans for a diamond reward, Emily Brent recounts the fateful past of her former maid, Beatrice Taylor, and General MacArthur succumbs to insanity, crippled with guilt over killing his subordinate and wife's lover, Arthur Richmond. After the General is found with his head smashed in with a telescope, the remaining seven realize that whoever left the mysterious message intends to make good on their threat, according to the rules of the [[Ten Little Indians|nursery rhyme]]. Wargrave proposes a damning theory to the others that the killer is one of them. After the butler, Mr Rogers, is found split open with an axe, and Miss Brent is impaled with one of her knitting needles, the five survivors band together to search all the rooms and belongings to unmask the killer and save themselves.\n| LineColor       = 9F260E\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = Episode 3\n| DirectedBy      = Craig Viveiros\n| WrittenBy       = Sarah Phelps\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2015|12|28|df=y}}\n| Viewers         = 8.33<ref name=\"BARB_Top30\"/><ref group=lower-alpha name=28day/>\n| ShortSummary    = Five of the original ten are left. Judge Wargrave is found, dressed up to match the Chancery verse of the poem, with a gunshot wound to the head. He is declared dead by Armstrong. The remaining four engage in a demented bacchanal with alcohol and drugs. Vera and Philip have sex. During the night, Armstrong leaves the house, leaving the other three to believe that he is the killer. Blore is ambushed and fatally stabbed by the killer wearing a bear skin rug. Subsequently, Armstrong's corpse is brought in by the tide. Vera manages to lift Philip's gun and when he charges at her, she shoots him dead. Delirious, she returns to her room where a noose is waiting. In a trance, she begins to hang herself. Then, Judge Wargrave walks in, quite alive, and reveals how he wanted to create an unsolvable mystery and punish the guilty, and how he intends to shoot himself to complete the poem. Vera tries to bargain with Wargrave, but he pulls the chair from under her and leaves her to die. He returns to the dining room, where he has set the table for two. He loads the revolver with the final bullet and shoots himself. The revolver recoils to land at the other table setting, thus creating a presumably unsolvable mystery for the police.\n| LineColor       =9F260E\n}}\n}}\n\n==Reception==\n''And Then There Were None'' received critical acclaim and was a ratings success for the BBC, with the first episode netting over 6 million viewers and becoming the second most watched programme on [[Boxing Day]]. Each of the two subsequent episodes netted over 5 million viewers.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jackson|first=Jasper|title=And Then There Were None helps BBC dominate Christmas ratings|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/dec/29/and-then-there-were-none-christmas-boxing-day-ratings-bbc-agatha-christie|date=29 December 2015|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], ''And Then There Were None'' has an approval rating of 92% based on 13 reviews, with an average rating of 7.5/10. The site's critics' consensus reads: \"Dark yet dashingly executed, ''And Then There Were None'' offers a brazenly misanthropic look at human nature.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/and_then_there_were_none/s01|title=And Then There Were None: Miniseries|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nDespite criticism ahead of the programme's launch from the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' that the production deviated from Agatha Christie's source material,<ref>{{cite news|title=What HAS the BBC done to Agatha Christie? Christmas viewers will be stunned by controversial new adaption featuring drugs, gruesome violence and the F-word|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-3357749/What-BBC-Agatha-Christie.html|work=Daily Mail|first=Chris|last=Hastings|date=12 December 2015|accessdate=29 December 2015}}</ref> ''And Then There Were None'' received critical acclaim. Ben Dowell of the ''[[Radio Times]]'' gave a positive review.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dowell|first=Ben|title=And Then There Were None is a creepy, chilling Agatha Christie... with a helping of Aidan Turner|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-12-26/and-then-there-were-none-is-a-creepy-chilling-agatha-christie-with-a-helping-of-aidan-turner|date=26 December 2015|work=[[Radio Times]]|location=London|accessdate=28 December 2015}}</ref> Jasper Reese for ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' gave the first episode 4 out of 5 stars, calling it a \"pitch-black psychological thriller as teasing murder mystery\" and \"spiffingly watchable\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Rees|first=Jasper|title=And Then There Were None, review: 'spiffingly watchable'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/12064725/And-Then-There-Were-None-review-spiffingly-watchable.html|date=26 December 2015|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nReviewing the first episode, UK daily newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s Sam Wollaston noted, \"[...] it also manages to be loyal, not just in plot but in spirit as well. I think the queen of crime would approve. I certainly do. Mass murder rarely gets as fun as this.\"<ref name=\"The Guardian 26 December 2015\">{{cite news|last=Wollaston|first=Sam|title= Dickensian review \u2013 a labour of love obscured by too much fog and too many hats|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/dec/26/dickensian-agatha-christie-and-then-there-were-none-review|date=26 December 2015|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London, UK|accessdate= 29 December 2015}}</ref> Reviewing the final episode for ''The Daily Telegraph'', Tim Martin gave it 4 out of 5 stars, calling it a \"class act\", and praising the adaptation for highlighting the darkness of Christie's novel, which he claimed no previous adaptation had attempted.<ref>{{cite news|last=Martin|first=Tim|title=And Then There Were None, episode three, review: 'a class act'|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/tv-and-radio-reviews/12071655/And-Then-There-Were-None-episode-three-review.html|date=28 December 2015|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London, UK|accessdate=29 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[And Then There Were None (disambiguation)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3581932|title=And Then There Were None}}\n* {{BBC programme}}\n*{{Rotten Tomatoes TV|and_then_there_were_none}}\n\n{{And Then There Were None}}\n\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2010s British television miniseries]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2015 British television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:British crime films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British mystery films]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1930s]]\n[[Category:Television programmes based on works by Agatha Christie]]\n[[Category:BBC television dramas]]\n[[Category:Television series by Mammoth Screen]]\n[[Category:Films based on And Then There Were None]]\n", "name_user": "Inan Bahadir", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/And_Then_There_Were_None_(miniseries)"}
{"title_page": "Training centre for release of the Atma-energy", "text_new": "'''Training centre for release of the Atma-energy''' (German: ''Trainingszentrum zur Freisetzung der Atmaenergie''<ref name=\"Schmid\">{{cite book |last1=Schmid |first1=Georg |last2=Eggenberger |first2=Oswald |title=Kirchen, Sekten, Religionen: religi\u00f6se Gemeinschaften, weltanschauliche Gruppierungen und Psycho-Organisationen im deutschen Sprachraum; ein Handbuch |year=2003 |publisher=Theologischer Verlag Z\u00fcrich |location=Z\u00fcrich |isbn=3-290-17215-5 |language=de |pages=269\u2013271}}</ref>), also known as ''Atman Foundation'', was a [[new religious movement]] active mainly on the island of [[Tenerife]] and in [[Germany]]. This sect was originally a splinter group of the [[Brahma Kumaris]]<ref name=\"Regulating Religion\">James T. Richardson (2004). ''Regulating Religion: Case Studies from Around the Globe''. {{ISBN|978-0-306-47887-1}}, p. 157. \"The case refers to the Atman Foundation (originally a splinter group from the Brahma Kumaris) and made international headlines on January 8, 1998 when it was announced that the Canary Islands police had prevented a mass suicide of \u201ca branch of the Solar Temple\u201d by arresting its leader. German motivational speaker Heide Fittkau\u2014Garthe. and a number of followers During subsequent months\u2018 the case disappeared from the international media. At the local level, it was clarified that the Atman Foundation has nothing to do with the Solar Temple but, according to a family of disgruntled German ex-members, may be \u201cjust as bad\". Police investigations in Germany failed to detect any evidence that the Foundation was preparing a mass suicide. However, the accusation is maintained in Spain at the time of this writing, together with some others, although no trial has been scheduled.\"</ref> and is known for a police and media scare in which an alleged attempt to commit ritual suicide took place in [[Teide National Park]] in Tenerife. \n\nApparently, the 32 members of the sect believed that they would be collected by a spacecraft and taken to an unspecified destination. Failing that, they were believed to be going to commit suicide.<ref>Rod Usher. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110522162815/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/1998/int/980119/europe.neardeath_experie15.html Near-Death Experience], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', January 19, 1998 Vol. 151 No. 3 Archived from [https://web.archive.org/web/20000816230815/http://www.time.com:80/time/magazine/1998/int/980119/europe.neardeath_experie15.html the original] on May 22, 2011</ref> However, more recent articles in ''Tenerife News'' and ''Diario de Avisos'' question this, saying there was no intention to commit suicide by the group.<ref name=\"remembering heidi\" /><ref name=\"Suicide with fruit juice\" />\n\nThe Spanish media referred to the group as \"secta de Heide Fittkau\", after the name of its founder.\n\n== History ==\nIt was founded by a German psychologist, Heide Fittkau-Garthe, who, on August 15, 1994 sold all her assets and moved to Tenerife.\n\nOn January 8, 1998, Fittkau-Garthe was alleged to have attempted suicide with her followers in Teide National Park, resulting in a police raid on the premises that the sect had in [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]].<ref name=\"hemeroteca.lavanguardia\">[http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.es/preview/1998/01/09/pagina-21/33817323/pdf.html La polic\u00eda frustra el suicidio colectivo de los 33 miembros de una secta en Tenerife] (La Vanguardia, 9 de enero de 1998)</ref>\n<ref name=\"remembering heidi\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021134/http://www.tenerifenews.com/cms/front_content.php?client=1&lang=1&idcat=70&idart=5389 Beam them up, Heidi - Remembering the Las Ca\u00f1adas suicide sect scare], Tenerife News Online, Retrieved, 2007-10-13</ref>\n\nAccording to Spanish and German police, the group was going to perform a sacrifice similar to that performed by the [[Order of the Solar Temple]] on October 4, 1994 in [[Cheiry]] and [[Salvan, Switzerland|Salvan]], two villages in [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"elpais\">[http://www.elpais.com/articulo/sociedad/SANTA_CRUZ_DE_TENERIFE/lider/secta/Tenerife/recaudo/300/millones/fieles/elpepisoc/19980118elpepisoc_5/Tes La l\u00edder de la secta de Tenerife recaud\u00f3 300 millones entre sus fieles]</ref> It was later clarified that the Atman Foundation had nothing to do with the Solar Temple.<ref name=\"Regulating Religion\" /> On the other hand, just three years later, in 1997 the [[Heaven's Gate (religious group)|Heaven's Gate]] sect, also committed a ritual suicide in [[San Diego, California]], these events alerted the police about the Heide sect.\n\nThe group was thought to be planning to drink fruit juice laced with poison which was confiscated during the raid. On analysis the fruit juice was found not to contain any poison. In Germany all charges were eventually dropped in against members of the group due to lack of evidence although the accusation still remained in Spain as of 2004 with no trial scheduled.<ref name=\"Suicide with fruit juice\">[http://archivo.diariodeavisos.com/epoca1/2004/04/21/hoy/noticias/tenerife/P40252A.html Suicidio colectivo con zumo de frutas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303201816/http://archivo.diariodeavisos.com/epoca1/2004/04/21/hoy/noticias/tenerife/P40252A.html |date=2016-03-03 }} Diario de avisos, 21 April 2004</ref><ref name=\"freed\">http://www.irishtimes.com/news/judge-frees-spaceship-cult-1.124111</ref><ref name=\"Regulating Religion\" /> The acquittal of Fittkau-Garthe in Spain received almost no attention in the news.<ref>{{cite book | first=Susan | last=Palmer |authorlink=Susan J. Palmer | title=The new heretics of France | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2011 | location=Oxford, New York | isbn=978-0-19-973521-1 | page=54}}</ref>\n\nWhen interviewed by a local daily, Fittkau-Garthe made the following statement, \"The group was no sect and I have never worked in one. I was accused of planning the suicide of a group of friends who had merely come over to spend Christmas in Tenerife. What actually happened in 1998 was the result of an act of a daughter's vengeance on her mother who was one of the group. Six months before they had had an enormous family row and it was the daughter who contacted Interpol and told them her mother and another hundred people were in the mountains of Tenerife intending to commit mass suicide. The daughter, she said, had informed the authorities that the group was a destructive sect. What happened was terrible. And the worst of it all were the lies that were told concerning children.\"<ref name=\"remembering heidi\" />\n\n== Beliefs ==\nAccording to Angela Gabriela a former member of the sect, the highlight of the ritual was the ''\"love ring\"''. This practice consisted of huge orgies, even between members of the same family.<ref name=\"laopinion\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20110613143130/http://www.laopinion.es/afondo/2009/11/12/heide-fittkau-anillo-amor/254082.html Heide Fittkau y el \"anillo del amor\"] La Opini\u00f3n de Tenerife, Archived June 13, 2011</ref>\n\nThere were two children in the sect, a boy of twelve and a girl of eight; apparently, the sect believed that when the eight-year-old girl turned sixteen she would beget [[Jesus]]. In an orgy she would be impregnated by one of the men of the sect and nobody would know who was to be the child's father.<ref name=\"laopinion\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Doomsday cult]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Apocalyptic groups]]\n[[Category:Brahma Kumaris]]\n[[Category:UFO religions]]\n[[Category:Hindu new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the Canary Islands]]\n[[Category:Religion in the Canary Islands]]\n", "text_old": "'''Training centre for release of the Atma-energy''' (German: ''Trainingszentrum zur Freisetzung der Atmaenergie''<ref name=\"Schmid\">{{cite book |last1=Schmid |first1=Georg |last2=Eggenberger |first2=Oswald |title=Kirchen, Sekten, Religionen: religi\u00f6se Gemeinschaften, weltanschauliche Gruppierungen und Psycho-Organisationen im deutschen Sprachraum; ein Handbuch |year=2003 |publisher=Theologischer Verlag Z\u00fcrich |location=Z\u00fcrich |isbn=3-290-17215-5 |language=de |pages=269\u2013271}}</ref>), also known as ''Atman Foundation'', was a [[new religious movement]] active mainly on the island of [[Tenerife]] and in [[Germany]]. This sect was originally a splinter group of the [[Brahma Kumaris]]<ref name=\"Regulating Religion\">James T. Richardson (2004). ''Regulating Religion: Case Studies from Around the Globe''. {{ISBN|978-0-306-47887-1}}, p. 157. \"The case refers to the Atman Foundation (originally a splinter group from the Brahma Kumaris) and made international headlines on January 8, 1998 when it was announced that the Canary Islands police had prevented a mass suicide of \u201ca branch of the Solar Temple\u201d by arresting its leader. German motivational speaker Heide Fittkau\u2014Garthe. and a number of followers During subsequent months\u2018 the case disappeared from the international media. At the local level, it was clarified that the Atman Foundation has nothing to do with the Solar Temple but, according to a family of disgruntled German ex-members, may be \u201cjust as bad\". Police investigations in Germany failed to detect any evidence that the Foundation was preparing a mass suicide. However, the accusation is maintained in Spain at the time of this writing, together with some others, although no trial has been scheduled.\"</ref> and is known for a police and media scare in which an alleged attempt to commit ritual suicide took place in [[Teide National Park]] in Tenerife. \n\nApparently, the 32 members of the sect believed that they would be collected by a spacecraft and taken to an unspecified destination. Failing that, they were believed to be going to commit suicide.<ref>Rod Usher. [https://web.archive.org/web/20110522162815/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/1998/int/980119/europe.neardeath_experie15.html Near-Death Experience], ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', January 19, 1998 Vol. 151 No. 3 Archived from [https://web.archive.org/web/20000816230815/http://www.time.com:80/time/magazine/1998/int/980119/europe.neardeath_experie15.html the original] on May 22, 2011</ref> However, more recent articles in ''Tenerife News'' and ''Diario de Avisos'' question this, saying there was no intention to commit suicide by the group.<ref name=\"remembering heidi\" /><ref name=\"Suicide with fruit juice\" />\n\nThe Spanish media referred to the group as \"secta de Heide Fittkau\", after the name of its founder.\n\n== History ==\nIt was founded by a German psychologist, Heide Fittkau-Garthe, who, on August 15, 1994 sold all her assets and moved to Tenerife.\n\nOn January 8, 1998, Fittkau-Garthe was alleged to have attempted suicide with her followers in Teide National Park, resulting in a police raid on the premises that the sect had in [[Santa Cruz de Tenerife]].<ref name=\"hemeroteca.lavanguardia\">[http://hemeroteca.lavanguardia.es/preview/1998/01/09/pagina-21/33817323/pdf.html La polic\u00eda frustra el suicidio colectivo de los 33 miembros de una secta en Tenerife] (La Vanguardia, 9 de enero de 1998)</ref>\n<ref name=\"remembering heidi\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021134/http://www.tenerifenews.com/cms/front_content.php?client=1&lang=1&idcat=70&idart=5389 Beam them up, Heidi - Remembering the Las Ca\u00f1adas suicide sect scare], Tenerife News Online, Retrieved, 2007-10-13</ref>\n\nAccording to Spanish and German police, the group was going to perform a sacrifice similar to that performed by the [[Order of the Solar Temple]] on October 4, 1994 in [[Cheiry]] and [[Salvan, Switzerland|Salvan]], two villages in [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"elpais\">[http://www.elpais.com/articulo/sociedad/SANTA_CRUZ_DE_TENERIFE/lider/secta/Tenerife/recaudo/300/millones/fieles/elpepisoc/19980118elpepisoc_5/Tes La l\u00edder de la secta de Tenerife recaud\u00f3 300 millones entre sus fieles]</ref> It was later clarified that the Atman Foundation had nothing to do with the Solar Temple.<ref name=\"Regulating Religion\" /> On the other hand, just three years later, in 1997 the [[Heaven's Gate (religious group)|Heaven's Gate]] sect, also committed a ritual suicide in [[San Diego, California]], these events alerted the police about the Heide sect.\n\nThe group was thought to be planning to drink fruit juice laced with poison which was confiscated during the raid. On analysis the fruit juice was found not to contain any poison. In Germany all charges were eventually dropped in against members of the group due to lack of evidence although the accusation still remained in Spain as of 2004 with no trial scheduled.<ref name=\"Suicide with fruit juice\">[http://archivo.diariodeavisos.com/epoca1/2004/04/21/hoy/noticias/tenerife/P40252A.html Suicidio colectivo con zumo de frutas] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303201816/http://archivo.diariodeavisos.com/epoca1/2004/04/21/hoy/noticias/tenerife/P40252A.html |date=2016-03-03 }} Diario de avisos, 21 April 2004</ref><ref name=\"freed\">http://www.irishtimes.com/news/judge-frees-spaceship-cult-1.124111</ref><ref name=\"Regulating Religion\" /> The acquittal of Fittkau-Garthe in Spain received almost no attention in the news.<ref>{{cite book | first=Susan | last=Palmer |authorlink=Susan J. Palmer | title=The new heretics of France | publisher=Oxford University Press | year=2011 | location=Oxford, New York | isbn=978-0-19-973521-1 | page=54}}</ref>\n\nWhen interviewed by a local daily, Fittkau-Garthe made the following statement, \"The group was no sect and I have never worked in one. I was accused of planning the suicide of a group of friends who had merely come over to spend Christmas in Tenerife. What actually happened in 1998 was the result of an act of a daughter's vengeance on her mother who was one of the group. Six months before they had had an enormous family row and it was the daughter who contacted Interpol and told them her mother and another hundred people were in the mountains of Tenerife intending to commit mass suicide. The daughter, she said, had informed the authorities that the group was a destructive sect. What happened was terrible. And the worst of it all were the lies that were told concerning children.\"<ref name=\"remembering heidi\" />\n\n== Beliefs ==\nAccording to Angela Gabriela a former member of the sect, the highlight of the ritual was the ''\"love ring\"''. This practice consisted of huge orgies, even between members of the same family.<ref name=\"laopinion\">[http://www.laopinion.es/afondo/2009/11/12/heide-fittkau-anillo-amor/254082.html Heide Fittkau y el \"anillo del amor\"] La Opini\u00f3n de Tenerife</ref>\n\nThere were two children in the sect, a boy of twelve and a girl of eight; apparently, the sect believed that when the eight-year-old girl turned sixteen she would beget [[Jesus]]. In an orgy she would be impregnated by one of the men of the sect and nobody would know who was to be the child's father.<ref name=\"laopinion\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Doomsday cult]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Apocalyptic groups]]\n[[Category:Brahma Kumaris]]\n[[Category:UFO religions]]\n[[Category:Hindu new religious movements]]\n[[Category:Organisations based in the Canary Islands]]\n[[Category:Religion in the Canary Islands]]\n", "name_user": "Xndrrdnx", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced citation \"laopinion\" dead link with archive link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Training_centre_for_release_of_the_Atma-energy"}
